{"insight":"Sometimes the question is the grip","publicTitle":"When Letting Go Becomes Self-Inspection","plainSummary":"Some paths free us by ending the search, not by proving that nothing remains.","atAGlance":"Sometimes freedom begins when the inspection stops. A person can turn letting go into another way to measure the self. Some teachings do not answer what remains because they reject the chase that made the question feel necessary. The test is whether practice makes a person kinder and freer, or only more watchful of themselves.","keyPoints":["Letting go can mean ending the search, not finding what is left.","The risk is endless checking for purity, emptiness, or spiritual success.","Test whether practice brings more ease, honesty, and care."],"match":["some paths"],"tags":["letting go","practice","self-checking"]}
